<BlogLayout
  title="My First Sail Was a Category-One Storm"
  description="Halifax to Antigua aboard CSM. 70-knot winds, waves taller than the mast seemed, and a crash course in what marine fabrication actually needs to survive."
  datePublished="2025-05-20"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>I Didn't Grow Up Sailing</h2>

  <p>
    Let me be clear about something: I'm a mechanic from Atlantic Canada. I grew up around engines, not sails. The first time I stepped onto a sailboat with any intention of going offshore, it was to crew on a delivery from Halifax to Antigua. I thought I knew what I was getting into. I did not.
  </p>

  <p>
    The boat was solid. The crew was experienced — except for me. I was there because I could fix things, and on a boat crossing the Atlantic, someone who can fix things is worth their weight in spare parts.
  </p>

  <h2>The Storm</h2>

  <p>
    Three days out of Halifax, we sailed straight into a system that had no business being as angry as it was. The weather briefing said 30 knots. We got 70. The seas built to the point where you couldn't see anything from the trough — just walls of dark green water on every side.
  </p>

  <p>
    Category-one storm conditions. The boat was screaming. Everything that wasn't lashed down became a projectile. A winch handle came loose and put a dent in the cockpit coaming. The head door ripped off its hinges. A stanchion bent 45 degrees when a wave hit the rail.
  </p>

  <p>
    I spent hours below, wedged into the nav station, listening to the hull flex and creak while trying to keep my dinner down. Fear is a strong word, but I'll use it. I was scared. The ocean doesn't care about you.
  </p>

  <h2>What Broke</h2>

  <p>
    After the storm passed, the damage inventory started. And this is where my brain started connecting dots between sailing and fabrication:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Three plastic fairleads cracked clean through — UV-degraded PLA wouldn't have survived a calm day, let alone this.</li>
    <li>A mounting bracket for the radar reflector sheared its bolts — bad material choice, bad geometry.</li>
    <li>The companionway washboard warped from water pressure and wouldn't seat properly anymore.</li>
    <li>Cable ties used as structural fasteners (they weren't structural anymore).</li>
    <li>A nav light housing crumbled — injection-molded ABS that had been in the sun for eight years.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Every single failure was a materials problem or a design problem. Not a "the ocean is too strong" problem. The ocean is always that strong. The parts need to match.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Taught Me About Fabrication</h2>

  <p>
    That crossing rewired how I think about 3D printing. Before that trip, I was printing parts the way most people do — PLA, default settings, looks good on the desk. After Antigua, I started asking different questions:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Will this part survive UV exposure for three years?</li>
    <li>What happens when it's soaked in saltwater for a week straight?</li>
    <li>Can it handle cyclic loading — thousands of repeated stress cycles from wave action?</li>
    <li>What's the failure mode? Does it crack, deform, or crumble?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Those questions changed everything. They pushed me toward ASA, toward carbon-fiber-filled PETG, toward engineering-grade materials that actually perform in hostile environments. They're the reason 3D3D exists the way it does today — not as a printing service, but as a fabrication company that understands where these parts are going.
  </p>

  <h2>Respect the Environment</h2>

  <p>
    The ocean will test every part you make. Salt, sun, vibration, impact, temperature swings from freezing spray to tropical heat. If your part can survive offshore sailing, it can survive anything. That's the standard I build to now.
  </p>

  <p>
    I'm glad my first sail was a storm. A calm crossing would have taught me nothing. The storm taught me that parts either work or they don't, and the difference is material science, not luck.
  </p>
